 	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Node-link and matrix-based graphs are graphs made of nodes and edges. Those graphs are used to represent</span><strong><em> causal relationship </em></strong><span style="font-weight: 400;">between two or more variables. The node-link graph displayed in figure 1.1 has two nodes : &ldquo;having fun&rdquo; and &ldquo;good memories&rdquo;, and one edge between them which points towards &ldquo;good memories&rdquo;. When reading this graph one would say: &ldquo;Having fun causes good memories&rdquo;.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<img src="/img/trainging11.PNG"></img>
	
	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">These graphs are also used to show </span><strong><em>causal paths</em></strong><span style="font-weight: 400;"> or</span><strong><em> indirect relationships</em></strong><span style="font-weight: 400;"> between factors. For example Figure 1.2 shows that &ldquo;playing games&rdquo; causes &ldquo;having fun&rdquo; which causes &ldquo;good memories&rdquo;. At the same time &ldquo;playing games&rdquo; causes &ldquo;procrastination&rdquo;, which causes &ldquo;dissatisfaction&rdquo;. These are two different </span><strong>causal paths</strong><span style="font-weight: 400;">. Therefore, &ldquo;playing games&rdquo; </span><strong>indirectly causes</strong><span style="font-weight: 400;"> &ldquo;dissatisfaction&rdquo; and &ldquo;good memories&rdquo;.</span></p>
<p><br /><br /></p>
	<img src="/img/training12.PNG"></img>

	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The same information can also be displayed in a </span><strong>matrix-based graph </strong><span style="font-weight: 400;">(Figure 1.3). The darker squares on the matrix represents an edge between the row factor (horizontal label, on the left) and the column factor (vertical label, at an angle), which are the nodes of the matrix based-graph. For example, &ldquo;playing games&rdquo; (horizontal) causes &ldquo;having fun&rdquo; (vertical). Then if we are looking for a path we will look for factors that are caused by &ldquo;having fun&rdquo;. In order to do this we find the &ldquo;having fun&rdquo; factor on the left and will find the column factor that it is connected with, which is &ldquo;good memories&rdquo;. This way the same causal path is found: playing games -&gt; having fun -&gt; good memories. </span></p>
<p><br /><br /></p>
<img src="/img/training13.PNG"></img>
<p><br /><br /></p>

<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">To see that one factor can lead to different causal paths, we need to find the row factor (node) that has more than one darker squares (edges). The left side label is the beginning of the edge while the label at the top is the end of an edge. In this example, this is playing games. Please, find the the row &ldquo;playing games&rdquo; and find what are two different factors that it can lead to. As previously mentioned those are &ldquo;having fun&rdquo; and &ldquo;procrastination&rdquo;.</span></p>
