<h1> Colliders and Confounders </h1>

Colliders and confounders are types of structures that can introduce biases when reading causal graphs. These structures are not fixed in a graph. They appear according to a specific path. In order to show you a particular path later in the experiment there will be edges which will have thicker lines (highlighted lines). Regular drinking -> depression -> poor education -> negative parenting is an example of a highlighted path and can be seen bellow.

<p><br /><br /></p>
<img src="/img/highlight.PNG"></img>
<p><br /><br /></p>

Colliders and confounders can also be found in matrix-based graphs. The following graph represents the same logical structure. The beginning of a causal path is marked in <b>blue</b> and the end in <b>red</b>. The highlighted path is represented by darker squares. Each darker square represents an edge and each label represents a node.

<p><br /><br /></p>
<img src="/img/matrixHigh.PNG"></img>
<p><br /><br /></p>

In Figure 2.1. in the path boredom -> video grames -> fun, &ldquo;inability to focus&rdquo; is a <b>confounder</b> as it causes two of the factors on the graph. 

<p><br /><br /></p>
<img src="/img/confounder.PNG"></img>
<p><br /><br /></p>

 The same representation can be made in a matrix-based graph. if you start reading the graph from  &ldquo;boredom&rdquo; (the beginning of the graph/blue factor), you will quickly find that  &ldquo;fun&rdquo; (red factor) is the end of that path. If you look at the inability to focus label you will see that it causes boredom and video games, which are two of the nodes on the specified path. Therefore, it is is a confounder on this particular path.

<p><br /><br /></p>
<img src="/img/matrixTraining.PNG"></img>
<p><br /><br /></p>

In Figure 2.2 &ldquo;inability to focus&rdquo; has become a <b>collider</b> as two of the nodes on the specified path cause &ldquo;inability to focus&rdquo;. 
<p><br /><br /></p>
<img src="/img/collider.PNG"></img>
<p><br /><br /></p>


The graph bellow show the same representation but in a matrix-based graph. When the path from blue to red is followed, one can see that two nodes from the path cause &ldquo;inability to focus&rdquo;. Therefore, it is a collider.

<p><br /><br /></p>
<img src="/img/matrixCollider.PNG"></img>
<p><br /><br /></p>

In addition, colliders and confounders can be implicit. In Figure 2.3. on the association path boredom -> video games -> fun, inability to focus is again a confounder because it causes two of the nodes on the path. 

<p><br /><br /></p>
<img src="/img/assConfounder.PNG"></img>
<p><br /><br /></p>


In the graph below is the same: &ldquo;inability to focus&rdquo; is an implicit confounder. The blue colour helps us understand that the path starts from boredom even though inability to focus causes boredom. Then when we continue reading the graph we see that inability to focus also causes video games, which in turn causes fun. Therefore, &ldquo;inability to focus&rdquo; causes two factors in the causal path we are interested in and, therefore, it is a confounder. Figure 2.3 represents the same logical structure but in node-link visualisation.

<p><br /><br /></p>
<img src="/img/matrixImplicitConfounder.PNG"></img>
<p><br /><br /></p>


Similarly, there are implicit colliders (Figure 2.4). 

<p><br /><br /></p>
<img src="/img/assCollider.PNG"></img>
<p><br /><br /></p>


The graph below, &ldquo;inability to focus&rdquo; is an implicit collider. You can see that there is no explicit causal link between boredom and video games but both of them cause inability to focus creating the same structure as in Figure 2.4.

<p><br /><br /></p>
<img src="/img/matrixImplicitCollider.PNG"></img>
<p><br /><br /></p>



